@node "Installing" "Installing"

                            @{u}Installing@{uu}

An Installer script is provided which installs the script and/or the
documentation (@{i}this guide@{ui}) to wherever you wish it. Integrating it with
YAM is something you have to do on your own though.

MIMEhandlerII has been written to be triggered upon @{b}When reading a
message@{ub} in the ARexx folder of YAM's configuration. It can however
be interfaced with YAM through for instance its ARexx menu just as
well.

For information on how to set this up I suggest looking in YAM's
documentation on @{"Configuration/ARexx" link "YAM:YAM.guide/CO13"} and @{"Configuration/MIME" link "YAM:YAM.guide/CO11"}.

@{b}Wait for termination@{ub} should be left unticked.

Before starting the script there are a few @{"options" link "Configuration"} you would
probably want to set.
@endnode

@node "Configuration" "Configuration"

                          @{u}Configuration@{uu}

The configuration have been implemented with extra care that it is
easy to change and at the same time powerful. I believe I have managed
this successfully. The configuration itself is changed within the
script. It is important @{u}not@{uu} to change the format of the config for it,
without being too technical, relies on certain elements found in it, to
read it properly.

The below may seem mind-boggling at first but having read it all from
start to end it should become clear.

Currently there are three templates, which when used are substituted
with what they stand for:

 @{b}%s@{ub} - Actual pathname of the attached file. Where YAM
      saves it after having decoded it. Usually in T:
 @{b}%n@{ub} - Pseudo filename. What the user sees the file as
      being named as within YAM.
 @{b}%w@{ub} - @{i}(For archived files only)@{ui}. Where the archive
      should be extracted to.

It might be wise to enclose the above templates in double quotes (@{b}"@{ub})
to take care of any existing spaces within the filename.

In conjunction with the above templates these below options are
available. Commands must be enclosed in single quotes (@{b}'@{ub}). Most of
them represent buttons which are capitalized with the first available
letter not already taken used as shortcut. @{b}DELETE/S@{ub} and @{b}CANCEL/S@{ub} have
been left out on purpose for they are always present.

 @{b}VIEW/K@{ub}    - Sets the command to view the attached file.
 @{b}EXTRACT/K@{ub} - @{i}(For archived files only)@{ui}. Sets the
             command to extract files from an archive.
 @{b}SAVE/S@{ub}    - Gives the option to save the file. The default
             viewer will use it as well.
 @{b}CON/S@{ub}     - Gives the option to direct output to the CON device.

With that said let us move on to the different options currently
available with their respective default applied.

@{b}default_viewer = 'multiview "%s"'@{ub}

   This sets the default viewer which is used when the attached file
   could not be identified.

@{b}con_output = '>CON:0/11/640/150/Output/WAIT/CLOSE'@{ub}

   Sets the addition to a command executed when using the @{b}CON@{ub} switch.
   It could for instance be changed to any other con device you might
   feel more comfortable with.

@{b}show_first = 'no'@{ub}

   Usually the first attached file is the message itself. This gives
   the choice to show it or not.

After having set those above options you get on with the fun part, the
different MIME parts. You add more using this format:

 @{b}<Maintype> / <Subtype / #?> OPTION [OPTION...]@{ub}

For instance this is how one could look:

 @{b}text/html VIEW 'htmlview "%s"' SAVE@{ub}

If wishing to use a wildcard such as this...

 @{b}text/#? VIEW 'multiview "%s"' SAVE@{ub}

...it must appear before any other MIME type of the same maintype, in
this instance @{i}text@{ui}.

To be able to handle lha archives easily this option could be used:

 @{b}application/x-lha VIEW 'lha v "%s"' EXTRACT 'lha -arx x "%s" "%w"' CON@{ub}

If for instance by pressing the view button should move images to the
RAM device this could be used, no matter how silly this may seem, it
serves only as an example:

 @{b}image/#? VIEW 'move FROM "%s" TO "ram:%n"'@{ub}
@endnode

